    <article class="prose-editorial cs-body" set:html={`<h2><b>Educational Case Study Disclosure</b></h2><p>This case study is hypothetical and for educational purposes only. Scenarios, borrower profiles, loan terms, interest rates, and outcomes are illustrative examples and do not represent current offers or guaranteed terms.</p><p>For specific details including down payment requirements, closing cost estimates, interest rate details, closing cost breakdowns, payment calculations, cash-to-close estimates, or an official Loan Estimate, it is highly recommended you<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a meeting with one of our licensed mortgage advisors</a>.</p><p><b>Learn more:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/24/">DSCR loan cash-out refinance Reg Z advertising requirements (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB official regulation</li><li><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1026">DSCR loan cash-out refinance Reg Z full text and compliance</a> – Electronic Code of Federal Regulations</li><li><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/interp-24/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Official DSCR loan cash-out refinance advertising interpretations (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB interpretations</li><li><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1014" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DSCR loan cash-out refinance MAP Rule (Reg N) mortgage advertising</a> – Mortgage advertising rules</li><li><a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/">NMLS Consumer Access – Verify DSCR loan cash-out refinance lender licensure</a></li></ul><p>Actual loan terms vary by credit profile, property, occupancy, location, market conditions, and lender guidelines. For current options tailored to you,<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a consultation</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> apply online</a>.</p><p>Ready to explore your options?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor.</p>		
					<h2>How This DSCR Cash-Out Refinance Leveraged Appreciation to Accelerate Portfolio Growth</h2>				
		<p>Thomas M., a 45-year-old entrepreneur in Tampa, had been building his rental property portfolio systematically over the past twelve years. He owned four single-family homes generating strong cash flow—properties he'd purchased strategically in neighborhoods experiencing steady appreciation. His real estate investments had performed exactly as planned: tenants paid mortgages through rent while property values climbed consistently, building substantial equity in each property.</p><p>Thomas's first rental property—purchased years ago during a market downturn—had appreciated dramatically. He'd purchased the three-bedroom home in an emerging Tampa neighborhood at an attractive price, and the property's value had grown substantially as the area gentrified with new restaurants, shops, and young professional residents. The property now had significant equity: appreciation plus years of mortgage paydown by tenants created a large gap between current value and remaining loan balance.</p><p>Thomas saw this appreciation equity as trapped capital that could accelerate his wealth-building strategy. He wanted to purchase his fifth rental property to continue scaling toward his goal of ten cash-flowing properties by age 55. The challenge was funding the down payment. Thomas could liquidate investment accounts, but that would trigger capital gains taxes and interrupt compound growth. He could deplete cash reserves, but that would leave him vulnerable to unexpected expenses across his growing property portfolio.</p><p>The optimal strategy was clear: access the equity in his first rental property through cash-out refinancing, using that capital to fund the down payment on property number five while maintaining the cash flow on property number one. The obstacle was that traditional cash-out refinances require extensive personal income documentation—tax returns showing all his business ventures, profit and loss statements, employment verification—creating the same documentation burden that had complicated his previous investment property purchases.</p><p>That's when Thomas discovered DSCR loan cash-out refinancing—a program that would let him access rental property equity without personal income documentation, qualifying based purely on the property's rental income.</p><p><b>Facing similar challenges?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to explore your options.</p><h2><b>The Challenge: Accessing Rental Property Equity Without Documentation Burden</b></h2><p>Thomas had experienced traditional investment property financing repeatedly through his four existing rental purchases. Every transaction involved extensive documentation of his entrepreneur income from multiple business ventures—creating time-consuming, complex underwriting processes that delayed closings and frustrated Thomas with their focus on irrelevant personal income details rather than property cash flow.</p><h3><b>Why Do Traditional Cash-Out Refinances Require Personal Income Documentation?</b></h3><p>The first challenge was the documentation burden of traditional cash-out refinancing. Thomas knew that conventional cash-out refinances on investment properties require the same extensive personal income verification as purchase mortgages: two years of tax returns including all schedules, year-to-date profit and loss statements for his businesses, verification of all income sources, explanation of any income variations, and detailed debt-to-income calculations factoring in all his business and personal debts.</p><p>As an entrepreneur with multiple business interests, Thomas's tax returns were complex. He operated several ventures generating income in different ways—some as W-2 income from his main business, some as 1099 contracting income, some as passive business income from partnerships. His accountant structured his finances for tax efficiency, using legitimate deductions that minimized tax liability but also reduced the income shown on his returns—making him appear to earn less than he actually did to mortgage underwriters.</p><p>"I'd already been through this documentation nightmare four times with my existing rental purchases," Thomas explained. "Every time I needed investment property financing, I spent weeks gathering documents, writing explanation letters, and arguing with underwriters who didn't understand how entrepreneur income works. The irony was that none of this personal income documentation mattered—my tenants pay the mortgages through rent, not me through my business income. But traditional lenders couldn't see past their obsession with personal income verification."</p><h3><b>How Does Portfolio Complexity Complicate Traditional Cash-Out Refinancing?</b></h3><p>The second obstacle was portfolio complexity. With four existing rental properties, Thomas's personal finances were intricate. His tax returns showed rental income and expenses for all four properties, depreciation schedules, various deductions, passive income, and active income—creating a complicated picture that traditional underwriters struggled to evaluate efficiently. Each rental property's income reduced his debt-to-income ratio slightly, but lenders discounted rental income substantially and counted each mortgage as debt, often resulting in artificially constrained borrowing capacity.</p><p>Moreover, Thomas wanted to refinance just one property to access its appreciation equity—but traditional lenders would evaluate his entire financial situation including all four rental properties, his primary residence, his businesses, and his personal debts. This comprehensive analysis took substantial time and created opportunities for underwriting complications unrelated to the property being refinanced.</p><h3><b>What Timeline Challenges Do DSCR Cash-Out Refinances Solve?</b></h3><p>The third challenge was timeline and efficiency. Thomas had identified his fifth investment property—a perfect addition to his portfolio in a high-demand Tampa rental market. He needed to fund the down payment quickly to secure the property before losing it to other investors. Traditional cash-out refinancing requiring extensive income documentation could take extended periods—periods during which Thomas might lose the fifth property opportunity he'd carefully identified.</p><p>"Time matters in investment property acquisition," Thomas said. "I'd found property number five with excellent cash flow potential in a strong rental market. I needed capital from property one's equity to fund property five's down payment. Traditional cash-out refinancing would require months of documentation, underwriting delays, and potential complications—during which I'd likely lose property five to faster-moving investors. I needed an efficient way to access my equity without the traditional documentation burden."</p><h3><b>Why Does Property Cash Flow Matter More Than Personal Income for Rental Refinancing?</b></h3><p>The fourth concern was the fundamental mismatch between what traditional lenders evaluated versus what actually mattered for investment property refinancing. Thomas wasn't refinancing to take cash out for personal use—he was refinancing to fund another investment property purchase, demonstrating sophisticated capital deployment rather than personal consumption. Yet traditional lenders would scrutinize his personal income extensively while giving limited attention to whether the property being refinanced generated sufficient rental income to support the new, larger mortgage.</p><p>"Investment property cash-out refinancing should focus on whether the property can support the new mortgage through rental income," Thomas explained. "Property one generates strong rent. Even after cash-out refinancing, the rent would still cover the new mortgage payment comfortably with positive cash flow. My personal income is irrelevant to whether that refinance makes financial sense. I needed financing that evaluated the property's cash flow rather than getting lost in my complex entrepreneur tax returns."</p><p><b>Experiencing similar frustration accessing rental property equity?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to discuss alternatives.</p><h2><b>The Discovery: How Thomas Found DSCR Cash-Out Refinance Solutions</b></h2><p>Thomas's investment property mentor—an experienced investor with fifteen rental properties—mentioned he'd recently completed a DSCR cash-out refinance to access appreciation equity from one of his oldest rentals. The mentor explained that DSCR lenders evaluate cash-out refinances based on the property's rental income relative to the new mortgage payment, completely eliminating personal income documentation requirements.</p><h3><b>What Makes DSCR Cash-Out Refinancing Different from Traditional Cash-Out Refinancing?</b></h3><p>Intrigued, Thomas scheduled a consultation with a DSCR loan specialist who explained how DSCR cash-out refinancing works fundamentally differently than traditional cash-out refinances. Instead of analyzing Thomas's tax returns, business income, employment, and debt-to-income ratios, the DSCR lender would focus on a single question: does the property generate enough rental income to support the new, larger mortgage payment after cash-out refinancing?</p><p>The DSCR lender would obtain a current rent estimate for the property, calculate the projected mortgage payment after cash-out refinancing (including principal, interest, taxes, insurance, and any HOA fees), and evaluate the debt service coverage ratio—the relationship between rent and payment. If the ratio met the DSCR lender's minimum threshold (demonstrating the property could support the new mortgage through rental income), the refinance qualified—regardless of Thomas's personal income complexity.</p><p>"That structure was exactly what I needed," Thomas explained. "The DSCR loan specialist confirmed that my tax returns, business income, and entrepreneur documentation were completely irrelevant to DSCR cash-out refinance qualification. What mattered was whether property one could continue generating strong rental income after refinancing—which it absolutely could. The rent far exceeded what the new payment would be even after taking out substantial equity. This was the efficient capital access strategy I needed."</p><h3><b>How Do DSCR Lenders Calculate Cash-Out Refinance Eligibility?</b></h3><p>The DSCR loan specialist walked through the specific mechanics. The property would be appraised to determine current market value. Thomas could refinance up to a specific loan-to-value ratio—accessing substantial equity while maintaining appropriate cushion. The new mortgage amount would be higher than the current balance, with the difference provided to Thomas at closing as cash-out proceeds he could immediately use to fund his fifth property purchase.</p><p>The DSCR lender would calculate the new mortgage payment including all components. A rent estimate would be obtained from the appraisal or third-party rent analysis. The ratio between rent and payment would be calculated. If that ratio met minimums, the DSCR cash-out refinance qualified. Simple, straightforward, and focused entirely on property cash flow rather than personal income complexity.</p><h3><b>What Qualification Factors Do DSCR Cash-Out Refinances Evaluate?</b></h3><p>The DSCR loan specialist explained other factors that would strengthen Thomas's DSCR cash-out refinance application. Excellent credit demonstrated financial responsibility. Substantial reserves proved Thomas could handle unexpected expenses or brief vacancy periods across his portfolio. Strong rental payment history on the property being refinanced showed the tenant situation was stable. These factors all made sense to Thomas—they measured actual risk factors without requiring complex personal income documentation.</p><p>The DSCR lender also explained rate considerations. DSCR cash-out refinance rates are typically appropriate for investment property financing—comparable to traditional investment property cash-out refinances but without the documentation burden. Thomas's strong financial profile would help him secure competitive rates within the DSCR lending space.</p><h3><b>Can DSCR Cash-Out Refinances Close Efficiently?</b></h3><p>Importantly, DSCR cash-out refinances close much faster than traditional cash-out refinances because they eliminate extensive personal income verification. Without needing to collect tax returns, profit and loss statements, employment verification, and debt-to-income documentation for complex entrepreneur situations, the underwriting process streamlines dramatically. For Thomas, who wanted to access equity quickly to fund his fifth property purchase, this timeline advantage was critical.</p><p>"DSCR cash-out refinancing solved every problem I had with traditional refinancing," Thomas said. "No personal income documentation. No entrepreneur tax return complexity. No weeks of back-and-forth with underwriters. The DSCR loan lender evaluated whether property one could support the new mortgage through rental income—which it easily could—and moved toward approval efficiently. This was the capital access strategy that would let me scale my portfolio without the documentation burden that had frustrated me in the past."</p><h2><b>The Solution: DSCR Cash-Out Refinance Approval and Capital Access</b></h2><p>Thomas worked with his DSCR loan specialist to structure cash-out refinancing for his first rental property. The process focused on the property's rental income, current market value, strong rent-to-payment ratio, Thomas's excellent credit, and his substantial reserves.</p><h3><b>What Documentation Do DSCR Cash-Out Refinances Require?</b></h3><p><b>Documentation provided:</b></p><ul><li>Excellent credit score demonstrating financial responsibility</li><li>Substantial cash reserves across rental property portfolio</li><li>Current rental lease demonstrating strong monthly rent</li><li>Rental payment history showing stable tenant and consistent income</li><li>Property information for appraisal and rent estimate</li><li>Existing mortgage information for payoff calculation</li><li>Bank statements showing reserves</li><li>No tax returns required</li><li>No employment verification needed</li><li>No profit and loss statements necessary</li><li>No personal income documentation requested</li><li>No debt-to-income calculations involving personal finances</li></ul><p><b>The approval process:</b></p><ol><li><b>Initial consultation</b> – Discussed DSCR cash-out refinance strategy and Thomas's portfolio goals</li><li><b>Property evaluation</b> – Analyzed property one's cash flow and appreciation equity</li><li><b>Loan structuring</b> – Calculated optimal loan amount balancing equity access and LTV ratio</li><li><b>Rent estimate obtained</b> – Appraiser provided current market rent estimate</li><li><b>Payment projection calculated</b> – DSCR lender projected new mortgage payment after cash-out</li><li><b>DSCR ratio evaluated</b> – Confirmed rent-to-payment ratio met minimum thresholds</li><li><b>Credit review</b> – Verified Thomas's excellent credit history</li><li><b>Reserve verification</b> – Confirmed substantial cash reserves across portfolio</li><li><b>Rental income documentation</b> – Obtained current lease and payment history</li><li><b>Property appraisal</b> – Licensed appraiser valued property showing substantial appreciation</li><li><b>Conditional approval</b> – DSCR cash-out refinance approved subject to standard conditions</li><li><b>Fifth property offer</b> – Thomas made offer on fifth investment property with DPA funds secured</li><li><b>Final approval</b> – All conditions cleared</li><li><b>Closing</b> – Thomas closed on DSCR cash-out refinance, accessing substantial equity</li></ol><p>The DSCR lender evaluated whether the property could support the new, larger mortgage through rental income. The rent estimate showed strong monthly income while the projected new payment was manageable—creating a comfortable DSCR ratio that easily met requirements. The substantial appreciation meant Thomas could access impressive equity while maintaining conservative loan-to-value ratios and strong property cash flow.</p><h3><b>How Much Equity Can DSCR Cash-Out Refinancing Access?</b></h3><p>The property appraisal confirmed dramatic appreciation since Thomas's original purchase years earlier. Combined with mortgage paydown from tenant payments, Thomas had built substantial equity. The DSCR lender could access a large portion of that equity while staying within appropriate LTV limits—providing more than enough capital to fund his fifth property down payment with funds remaining for reserves.</p><p>The DSCR lender offered competitive rates appropriate for investment property cash-out refinancing. While slightly higher than primary residence rates, the rates were comparable to traditional investment property cash-out refinances—with the substantial advantage of eliminating complex income documentation and accelerating the approval timeline.</p><p><b>Exploring refinance?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/refinance-or-heloc-inquiry/"> Submit a refinance inquiry</a> to compare your options.</p><h2><b>The Results: Thomas Leverages Equity to Purchase Fifth Rental Property</b></h2><p>Thomas closed on his DSCR cash-out refinance and received substantial proceeds at closing. He immediately used those funds as the down payment on his fifth rental property—a two-bedroom condo in a high-demand area near Tampa's expanding tech corridor. Within weeks, both properties were performing excellently: property one continued generating strong positive cash flow despite the larger mortgage, and property five was rented to a tech professional at attractive rates.</p><h3><b>What Results Did Thomas Achieve with DSCR Cash-Out Refinancing?</b></h3><p><b>Final outcome:</b></p><ul><li>Accessed substantial appreciation equity from property one through DSCR cash-out refinancing</li><li>No personal income documentation required—eliminated tax return, employment, profit and loss complexity</li><li>Competitive DSCR loan rates appropriate for investment property financing</li><li>Property one maintained strong positive cash flow with new, larger mortgage</li><li>Used cash-out proceeds to fund property five down payment</li><li>Closed DSCR cash-out refinance efficiently without documentation delays</li><li>Purchased fifth rental property immediately after accessing equity</li><li>Timeline: Efficient approval and closing supporting investment timeline</li><li>Properties: Property one (3BR/2BA) continued strong performance; Property five (2BR/2BA) immediately rented</li><li>Long-term plan: Scale to ten properties by age 55, continue leveraging appreciation equity for portfolio growth</li></ul><h3><b>How Does DSCR Cash-Out Refinancing Compare to Traditional Cash-Out Refinancing?</b></h3><p><b>Traditional cash-out refinance vs. DSCR cash-out refinance:</b></p><ul><li><b>Traditional approach:</b> Extensive personal income documentation, entrepreneur tax complexity, timeline delays</li><li><b>DSCR approach:</b> Property cash flow qualification, no personal income documentation, efficient closing</li><li><b>Tax return complexity:</b> ELIMINATED ✓</li><li><b>Entrepreneur income documentation:</b> NOT REQUIRED ✓</li><li><b>Business profit and loss statements:</b> UNNECESSARY ✓</li><li><b>Timeline efficiency:</b> DRAMATICALLY IMPROVED ✓</li><li><b>Portfolio scaling:</b> ACCELERATED ✓</li><li><b>Capital deployment:</b> OPTIMIZED ✓</li></ul><p>"The DSCR cash-out refinance transformed how I think about portfolio scaling," Thomas explained. "I'd been viewing the equity in my existing properties as trapped capital I couldn't easily access without documentation nightmares. DSCR cash-out refinancing showed me I can leverage appreciation equity efficiently to fund new acquisitions without personal income documentation burden. Property one continues cash-flowing beautifully with its new mortgage. Property five is already generating income. I turned trapped equity into productive capital that accelerated my portfolio growth—exactly the sophisticated leverage strategy I needed."</p><h3><b>What Are Thomas's Long-Term Portfolio Leverage Plans?</b></h3><p>Thomas now views his entire rental portfolio through a strategic leverage lens. As each property appreciates over the coming years, that appreciation equity can potentially be accessed through DSCR cash-out refinancing to fund additional acquisitions. This creates a compounding growth effect: properties appreciate, equity is accessed and deployed into new properties, those new properties appreciate and generate cash flow, their future equity can be accessed for additional growth, and the cycle continues.</p><p>Thomas's goal of ten rental properties by age 55 now feels not just achievable but potentially conservative. With five properties already acquired and a clear understanding of how to leverage appreciation equity efficiently through DSCR cash-out refinancing, Thomas can potentially accelerate his timeline. Each property adds cash flow. Each property builds equity. Each property's equity can eventually fund additional acquisitions.</p><p>Beyond property ten, Thomas is already thinking about properties eleven through twenty for his retirement years. The passive income from twenty cash-flowing rental properties would provide financial independence, generational wealth for his children, and the freedom to pursue interests beyond real estate investing.</p><p>"This DSCR cash-out refinance on property one funded property five—but more importantly, it revealed the strategic framework for scaling efficiently," Thomas said. "Properties one through four have all appreciated substantially. As I continue growing toward property ten, I can potentially use DSCR cash-out refinancing on properties two, three, and four to help fund properties six, seven, eight, nine, and ten—turning trapped appreciation equity into productive capital that accelerates my wealth-building timeline. This is the sophisticated leverage strategy that will help me achieve financial independence through real estate."</p><p><b>Ready to get started?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> Get approved</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a call</a> to discuss your situation.</p><h2><b>Exploring Other DSCR Cash-Out Refinance Options?</b></h2><p>While Thomas used DSCR cash-out refinancing to fund his fifth rental property purchase, DSCR cash-out refinances work for multiple scenarios:</p><ul><li>Purchasing first rental? See how investors use<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/dscr-loan/"> DSCR loans for initial investment property acquisitions</a></li><li>Need better terms? See how borrowers use<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/dscr-loan-refinance/"> DSCR refinance to improve rates on existing rentals</a></li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> to find success stories matching your situation</li></ul><h2><b>Key Takeaways for Real Estate Investors Using Leverage</b></h2><p><b>What Can Investors Learn from This DSCR Cash-Out Refinance Success?</b></p><ul><li><b>DSCR cash-out refinancing accesses rental property equity without personal income documentation</b>—qualification based purely on property rental income eliminates tax returns, employment verification, and complex entrepreneur income analysis (<a href="https://singlefamily.fanniemae.com/media/9391/display">Fannie Mae investor cash-out refinance guidelines for comparison</a>)</li><li><b>Appreciation equity becomes deployable capital</b>—substantial property appreciation over years can be accessed efficiently and deployed into additional investment property acquisitions, accelerating portfolio growth</li><li><b>Property cash flow remains strong after cash-out</b>—DSCR lenders ensure refinanced properties maintain positive cash flow by requiring rent-to-payment ratios that preserve income generation despite larger mortgages</li><li><b>Portfolio scaling accelerates through strategic leverage</b>—accessing equity from existing properties to fund new acquisitions creates compounding growth effects that dramatically improve wealth-building timelines</li><li><b>Entrepreneur income complexity eliminated</b>—self-employed investors, business owners, and professionals with variable income avoid documentation burden that complicates traditional cash-out refinancing</li><li><b>Timeline efficiency critical for investment opportunities</b>—DSCR cash-out refinances close faster than traditional refinances, allowing investors to access capital quickly and capitalize on time-sensitive property acquisitions</li><li><b>Think beyond single-property wealth building</b>—sophisticated investors view rental portfolios as interconnected systems where each property's appreciation equity can strategically fund additional acquisitions, creating multiplicative growth rather than linear accumulation toward financial independence through passive income</li></ul><p><b>Have questions about DSCR cash-out refinancing?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor experienced in investor leverage strategies.</p><h2><b>Alternative Loan Programs for Equity Access</b></h2><p>If a DSCR cash-out refinance isn't the perfect fit, consider these alternatives:</p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loan-refinance">DSCR Rate-and-Term Refinance</a> – Improve terms without accessing equity if cash-out not needed</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/investment-property-heloc">HELOC on Investment Property</a> – Flexible line of credit for accessing equity as needed</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-cash-out-refinance">Conventional Investment Property Cash-Out Refinance</a> – Traditional cash-out with personal income documentation</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/portfolio-loan/">Portfolio Loan</a> – Flexible financing across multiple investment properties</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/bridge-loan/">Bridge Loan</a> – Short-term financing for purchasing before refinancing existing property</li></ul><p><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/">Explore all loan programs</a> to find your best option.</p><h2><b>Helpful DSCR Cash-Out Refinance Resources</b></h2><p><b>Learn more about this loan program:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loan-cash-out-refinance">Complete DSCR Cash-Out Refinance Guide</a> - Detailed requirements and leverage strategies</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/dscr-cash-out-calculator">DSCR Cash-Out Calculator</a> - Calculate equity access and new cash flow</li></ul><p><b>Similar success stories:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/dscr-cash-out-refinance-portfolio">How an investor used DSCR cash-out refinance to fund fifth property</a></li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/dscr-cash-out-refinance-leverage">Entrepreneur leverages appreciation equity through DSCR cash-out refinancing</a></li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> - Browse by investment strategy</li></ul><p><b>External authoritative resources:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://singlefamily.fanniemae.com/media/9391/display">Fannie Mae investor cash-out refinance guidelines</a> - Traditional cash-out refinance standards for comparison</li><li><a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p527">IRS rental property basis and depreciation</a> - Tax implications of refinancing and equity access</li></ul><p><b>Ready to get started?</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stai